sailpoint.connector

Interface Connector

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractConnector, AbstractFileBasedConnector, DelimitedFileConnector, JDBCConnector

    public interface Connector
    The Connector interface allows IIQ to authenticate and read data from to enterprise applications. It can be used used to communicate with applications such as LDAP, JDBC Or SAP. There are several built in connectors, but the interface can be used to create Connectors for home-grown applications too.

    Connectors will return ResourceObjects to represent application objects. All ResourceObjects have a type that is either account or group. The definition of the object attributes will be defined by a Schema objects that holds a list of AttributeDefinitions. The individual AttributeDefinition objects define an attribute's type, name, description and value length.

    The AbstractConnector class provides many of the necessary services that span across all connectors. It is highly recommended that all connectors extend AbstractConnector instead implementing this interface directly. This will help avoid incompatibilities when changes are made to the interface from release to release.

    In some cases when a connector reads from a single source and defines objects that span multiple Applications they will also participate in generating Proxied Applications.

    In 5.2 many of the methods that were used to describe default Applications were deprecated and replaced with specified with Template applications defined in the ConnectorRegistry Configuration object.

    See Also:
    Connector.getProxiedApplication(String, Map), AbstractConnector, Application, AttributeDefinition, ResourceObject, Schema

        The name of the Configuration option used to configure the the scope of permissions that a connector should return.

        The value of this configuration attribute is a list of permission objects. The idea here, is to allow an option where we can scope only the "compliance relevant" permissions.

      • OP_ATTRIBUTE_NAMES

        static final java.lang.String OP_ATTRIBUTE_NAMES
        The name of an option to connector methods to indicate which attributes should be included on returned application objects.

        All methods support the following precedence when resolving which attributes should be returned from a connector.

        1. Check the options map for an attribute named "objectAttributeNames"(Connector.OP_ATTRIBUTE_NAMES). These attribute names must be found in the object's schema, any non-schema attributes will be ignored.
        2. If option is not specified, connectors should use the attributes defined in the object's schema map.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • OP_ALLOW_BRUTE_FORCE_SEARCH

        static final java.lang.String OP_ALLOW_BRUTE_FORCE_SEARCH
        An option that can be passed to iterateObjects() that specifies whether to perform a brute force filtering of objects when a filter is specified but the Connector does not support the SEARCH feature. If the Connector does not support SEARCH and this option is false or not specified, iterateObjects() should throw an exception. Note that setting this option to true can have a significant performance implication on applications that are slow and/or have many application objects of the requested type.
        See Also:

      • getIteratorPartitions

        java.util.List<Partition> getIteratorPartitions(java.lang.String objectType,
                                                int suggestedPartitionCount,
                                                Filter filter,
                                                java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> ops)
                                         throws ConnectorException
        Return the list of partitions for a connector.

        The partitions returned here are simple objects that hold a name, size, objectType, and an attributes map for additional information.

        Each connector needs to set a unique name to each partition (unique within the list) and the objectType.

        The caller will take each partition and treat it as a single unit of work that will be distributed among the cluster of servers and or threads.

        Each object in the list should contain enough about the partition so the calls to iterateObjects have information to process a single partition.

        The caller will give hints to the suggestedPartitionCount based on processors and cores but the Application config should ultimately determine how many partitions should be returned.

        Parameters:
        objectType - The type of object for which to return partitions.
        suggestedPartitionCount - The caller's suggested partition count, but the application config should ultimately determine the number of partitions.
        ops - Provides additional options in the form of a Map
        Returns:
        List of Objects used to configure each partition
        Throws:
        ConnectorException
        See Also:
        Partition, Connector.iterateObjects(Partition)

        CloseableIterator<ResourceObject> iterateObjects(Partition partition)

        Return an iterator over the objects defined in the Partition object. Typically this is called to return a subset of the objects. Callers of this methods will typically have called the getIteratorPartitions first, then call back to this method for each Partition it returns.
        Parameters:

        Returns:

      • getProxiedApplication

        Application getProxiedApplication(java.lang.String name,
                                  java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> options)
                           throws ConnectorException
        Create an Application object to represent a resource managed by a proxy connector. The object is not persistent and can be further modified prior to storage.

        This is relevant only for connectors that support the PROXY feature. Typically this is used for connectors to provisioning systems where the system can serve as an aggregate source for many applications, and maintain its own proprietary application model.

        This is intended for use by the Aggregator to auto-generate application definitions when aggregating from a provisioning system. If this returns null, Aggregator will make a default empty application.

        Throws:
        ConnectorException

      • provision

        ProvisioningResult provision(ProvisioningPlan plan)
                      throws ConnectorException,
                             GeneralException
        Execute a provisioning plan. The returned result object will contain a status indicating whether the request succeeded, failed, or needs to be retried. In the case of a retry, the implementation is allowed to make modifications to the passed plan in order to save state for the retry. The plan is therefore both an input and an output from this method.
        Throws:
        ConnectorException
        GeneralException

      • checkStatus

        ProvisioningResult checkStatus(java.lang.String id)
                        throws ConnectorException,
                               GeneralException
        New in 5.5 this method can be used by asynchronous provisioning implementations to check the status of a queued request.

        This method will be called if any of the results returned by the provision method are QUEUED and there is also requestId set on the result.

        This method will be called one time for each ProvisioningResult in the ProvisioningPlan. The plan can store results at either the plan, account request or the attribute request level.

        The returned result's errors and warnings will be merged back into the main project.

        Returning a null result will have no change on the request and it will remained queued.

        Parameters:
        id - The ID of the queued request.
        Returns:
        ProvisioningResult that indicates the current status of the request
        Throws:
        ConnectorException
        GeneralException
